    "content": "**AI & Robotics Snacks** - May 22, 2026\n\n---\n\n## 🧯 Trump blinked at the AI guardrail\n\nThe White House prepared the signing pens, then discovered that model reviews are regulation when the room contains enough billionaires.\n\n- **The delay:** AP says Trump called off a Thursday AI executive order hours before a planned ceremony with tech executives, arguing it could weaken America's AI lead over China.\n- **The plan:** the order would have created a voluntary framework for national-security vetting of advanced models before public release, including systems from Anthropic, OpenAI and Google.\n- **The tension:** Treasury officials had already warned Wall Street about Claude Mythos cybersecurity risks, while Commerce model-evaluation agreements have quietly appeared and vanished.\n\n*The policy stack now compiles only after a lobbyist pass.*\n\n**Sources:** [AP](https://apnews.com/article/trump-ai-executive-order-ee318f35acc8a2c43e47f3ebf26cb459) | [Axios](https://www.axios.com/2026/05/21/ai-news-cycle-openai-anthropic-spacex)\n\n---\n\n## 🏦 Washington turned AI into export finance\n\nThe AI race has reached the export-credit phase, because apparently models need loan guarantees now.\n\n- **The program:** Reuters says the U.S. Export-Import Bank is expected to approve ExportAI, a financing push for foreign purchases of American AI tools.\n- **The gate:** Commerce would need to sign off before sensitive exports, including advanced Nvidia-style chips, could receive financing support.\n- **The arsenal:** the package includes insurance, medium-term loan guarantees, direct loans and long-term guarantees, all aimed at pushing U.S. AI infrastructure abroad before China fills the shelf.\n\n*Nothing says frictionless innovation like a one-page financing memo with geopolitical intent.*\n\n**Sources:** [Reuters via Investing.com](https://www.investing.com/news/stock-market-news/trump-administration-seeks-to-supercharge-us-ai-exports-with-billions-in-financing-document-shows-4703193)\n\n---\n\n## 💸 OpenAI found revenue, then lost more than revenue\n\nCodex helped OpenAI print a very large top-line number, followed immediately by the traditional frontier-lab footnote: please ignore the furnace.\n\n- **The quarter:** PYMNTS, citing The Information, says OpenAI generated about $5.7 billion in Q1 revenue, nearly $1 billion more than Anthropic.\n- **The engine:** Codex, business sales and ChatGPT ad tests helped drive the quarter; OpenAI is still aiming for roughly $30 billion in 2026 revenue.\n- **The burn:** adjusted operating margin was negative 122%, meaning the company lost about $1.22 for every revenue dollar even after exclusions.\n\n*Growth is real. Profitability remains a distant rumored feature.*\n\n**Sources:** [PYMNTS](https://www.pymnts.com/artificial-intelligence-2/2026/openais-codex-helps-drive-nearly-6-billion-quarter/) | [Techmeme](https://www.techmeme.com/)\n\n---\n\n## 🎧 Spotify licensed the AI karaoke machine\n\nThe music industry has decided the safest AI cover is the one with a contract stapled to it.\n\n- **The deal:** Spotify and Universal Music Group agreed to let Premium users create AI-generated covers and remixes from participating UMG artists and songwriters.\n- **The product:** TechCrunch says the tool will be a paid add-on, with revenue shared with participating rightsholders; pricing and launch date were not disclosed.\n- **The positioning:** Spotify framed the product around consent, credit and compensation, a not-subtle contrast with Suno and Udio's lawsuit-first route through AI music.\n\n*The remix button finally has a legal department.*\n\n**Sources:** [TechCrunch](https://techcrunch.com/2026/05/21/spotify-and-universal-music-strike-deal-allowing-fan-made-ai-covers-and-remixes/) | [Spotify](https://newsroom.spotify.com/)"
  }
]
